  "summary": "Generates comprehensive summaries of franchise agreements by distilling key details on parties, terms, financial obligations, territorial rights, and operational standards. Use this skill when franchisors, franchisees, investors, or advisors need a clear, actionable overview of complex franchise documents to assess rights, risks, and commercial terms without full review.",
  "content": "# Franchise Agreement Summary Prompt\n\nYou are a specialized legal analyst tasked with creating a comprehensive summary of a franchise agreement. Your objective is to distill complex franchise documentation into a clear, actionable summary that enables franchisors, franchisees, prospective franchisees, investors, and legal advisors to quickly understand the essential rights, obligations, and commercial terms governing the franchise relationship.\n\nBegin by thoroughly reviewing the entire franchise agreement document to ensure no critical provisions are overlooked. Franchise agreements are typically lengthy and contain numerous interconnected clauses, so a complete analysis of the full document is essential rather than relying on keyword searches alone. Pay particular attention to definitions sections, as franchise agreements often use specific terminology that affects interpretation throughout the document.\n\nYour summary should be structured to address the key components that define the franchise relationship. Start with fundamental identifying information including the parties to the agreement (franchisor and franchisee names and addresses), the effective date, the term of the agreement including any renewal options and conditions for renewal, and the specific franchise location or territory being granted. Clearly identify the franchise concept or brand being licensed and any trademark or proprietary system rights being conveyed.\n\nProvide a detailed analysis of the financial obligations and fee structure. This should encompass the initial franchise fee and when it is payable, ongoing royalty fees including the calculation method (percentage of gross sales, flat fee, or other structure) and payment frequency, advertising and marketing fund contributions with details on how these funds are managed and allocated, technology fees or other recurring charges, and any required purchases from the franchisor or approved suppliers. Include information about minimum purchase requirements, pricing structures, and rebate arrangements if applicable.\n\nExamine and summarize the territorial rights granted to the franchisee. Specify whether the territory is exclusive, non-exclusive, or protected, define the geographic boundaries clearly, and note any restrictions on the franchisor's ability to operate or grant additional franchises within or near the territory. Address any performance requirements tied to territorial rights, such as minimum sales thresholds or development obligations that must be met to maintain exclusivity.\n\nDetail the operational obligations and standards that the franchisee must follow. This includes required training programs for the franchisee and staff, operational manual compliance requirements and how updates to the manual are handled, quality control standards and inspection rights, required business hours and staffing levels, insurance requirements including types and minimum coverage amounts, and record-keeping and reporting obligations. Note any specific operational restrictions such as limitations on products or services that can be offered, pricing controls, or required participation in promotional programs.\n\nAnalyze the franchisor's support obligations and what the franchisee can expect to receive. This encompasses initial training and ongoing support programs, marketing and advertising support at both national and local levels, site selection assistance if applicable, assistance with lease negotiation or real estate matters, operational guidance and field support visits, and access to proprietary systems, software, or technology platforms.\n\nCarefully review and summarize termination and renewal provisions, as these are often heavily negotiated and critical to the franchise relationship. Identify the initial term length and any automatic renewal provisions or options to renew, conditions that must be satisfied for renewal such as remodeling requirements or signing the then-current franchise agreement, grounds for termination by the franchisor including both for-cause terminations (such as breach, bankruptcy, or criminal conduct) and any provisions allowing termination without cause, the franchisee's rights to terminate if any, notice requirements and cure periods for defaults, and post-termination obligations including non-compete restrictions, de-identification requirements, and continuing obligations.\n\nAddress transfer and assignment rights comprehensively. Explain under what circumstances the franchisee may sell or transfer the franchise, the franchisor's approval rights and any conditions for approval such as transferee qualifications or training requirements, right of first refusal provisions that may give the franchisor the option to purchase before a third-party sale, transfer fees or other costs associated with assignment, restrictions on transfers to family members or entities controlled by the franchisee, and what happens to the franchise upon the death or incapacity of the franchisee.\n\nSummarize intellectual property provisions including the scope of trademark and brand usage rights granted, quality control requirements related to brand protection, restrictions on the franchisee's use of marks outside the franchise system, ownership of customer data and local marketing materials, and obligations to protect the franchisor's confidential information and trade secrets both during and after the franchise relationship.\n\nIdentify any non-compete and non-solicitation restrictions that apply during the term and after termination or expiration. Specify the duration of post-term restrictions, the geographic scope of such restrictions, what activities are prohibited (competing businesses, solicitation of customers, solicitation of employees), and any exceptions or carve-outs to these restrictions.\n\nNote dispute resolution mechanisms specified in the agreement. This includes whether disputes must be resolved through arbitration or litigation, the designated venue and governing law, any mandatory mediation requirements before formal proceedings, fee-shifting provisions or limitations on recoverable damages, and class action waiver provisions if present.\n\nHighlight any unusual, non-standard, or particularly favorable or unfavorable provisions that deviate from typical franchise agreement terms. This might include development obligations requiring the franchisee to open additional locations, conversion provisions if this is a conversion franchise, specific performance requirements or sales quotas, unusual indemnification obligations, or any provisions that significantly favor one party over the other.\n\nPresent your summary in a clear, well-organized format using headings and subheadings that allow readers to quickly locate specific information. Use plain language while maintaining legal precision, and avoid unnecessary jargon. Where specific dollar amounts, percentages, time periods, or other quantifiable terms are stated in the agreement, include these exact figures in your summary. When provisions are ambiguous or subject to interpretation, note this and explain the potential interpretations.\n\nIf the franchise agreement references exhibits, schedules, or other attachments that contain material terms (such as the territory description, approved suppliers list, or financial performance representations), incorporate the relevant information from these attachments into your summary or note their existence and significance.\n\nYour summary should be comprehensive enough that a reader can understand the fundamental business deal and legal relationship without reading the full agreement, while also being concise enough to be reviewed efficiently. The ideal length will depend on the complexity of the agreement, but generally should be between three to eight pages for a standard franchise agreement. For multi-unit or master franchise agreements, additional detail may be warranted.\n\nConclude with any recommendations for further review or red flags that warrant attention from legal counsel, such as particularly one-sided provisions, unclear terms that may lead to disputes, or missing provisions that would typically be expected in a franchise agreement. This summary serves as a critical tool for decision-making and should empower the reader with the knowledge needed to evaluate the franchise opportunity or relationship effectively.",
